            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>[Right column]: Herais, daughter of Herylos, farewell.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#AA">
                <p>Given the presence of at least two epitaphs, it is likely that this plaque belonged to a family tomb. Herylos is a unique name, not attested elsewhere. Brugnone (1974) suggests that it could be a form of the documented Heryllos, or is a derivative of the Latin Herylus. Herais is an extremely common name in the empire, attested in Sicily only in the masculine on a lead sheet at Kamarina, <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic030053">ISic030053</ref>.</p>
            </div>
